  "opinion": "As a 49-year-old hairdresser living in Philadelphia, I see fake content on social media a few times a week, and it's something I take seriously, especially as an immigrant and a Muslim who values truth and community. In my salon, I hear all sorts of stories from clients, and I've learned that not everything online is real—just like not every hairstyle suits everyone. My approach is straightforward: I don't share or believe things without checking first. For example, if I see a post about a football match or a health tip, I might ask a friend or look it up on reliable sites before passing it on. I think social media platforms should do more to flag fake news, but as users, we have a role too. Being extraverted, I enjoy chatting with people online, but I stay cautious and encourage others to do the same. With my moderate openness, I'm willing to learn new ways to spot lies, like using fact-checking tools. My low conscientiousness means I'm not overly strict, but I try to keep my feed clean by following trusted sources, like local news or community groups. As a father, I worry about my child seeing false information, so I talk to them about being smart online. Overall, I believe in staying informed, questioning what I see, and spreading kindness instead of rumors.",
